    "keyRecommendations": "Screen all patients with neck pain for serious pathology (infection, cancer, cardiac involvement, arterial insufficiency, upper cervical ligamentous insufficiency, cranial nerve dysfunction, fracture) and refer as indicated (Grade A). Use validated self-report questionnaires to identify baseline status and monitor pain, function, disability, and psychosocial functioning (Grade A). Use existing appropriateness criteria for imaging referral decisions in traumatic and nontraumatic neck pain (Grade A). Assess impairments of body function including: cervical AROM, cervical flexion-rotation test, cervical/thoracic segmental mobility (mobility deficits); neurodynamic testing, Spurling's test, distraction test, Valsalva test (radiating pain); cranial cervical flexion and neck flexor endurance tests (movement coordination impairments); and pressure pain threshold via algometry (Grade B). Classify patients into: neck pain with mobility deficits, movement coordination impairments (including WAD), headaches (cervicogenic), or radiating pain (Grade C). MOBILITY DEFICITS — Acute: thoracic manipulation, neck ROM exercises, scapulothoracic and upper extremity strengthening (Grade B); may add cervical manipulation/mobilization (Grade C). MOBILITY DEFICITS — Subacute: neck and shoulder girdle endurance exercises (Grade B); may add thoracic and cervical manipulation/mobilization (Grade C). MOBILITY DEFICITS — Chronic: multimodal approach including thoracic + cervical manipulation/mobilization, mixed neuromuscular/stretching/strengthening/endurance/aerobic/cognitive-affective exercise, and dry needling, laser, or intermittent traction (Grade B). MOVEMENT COORDINATION IMPAIRMENTS (WAD) — Acute: educate to return to normal activities ASAP, minimize collar use, perform postural and mobility exercises; reassure recovery expected within 2-3 months (Grade B). MOVEMENT COORDINATION IMPAIRMENTS (WAD) — Subacute: multimodal manual mobilization plus exercise; monitor for delayed recovery needing more intensive rehab and early pain education (Grade B/F); may use single-session advice/exercise/education, comprehensive exercise program, or TENS (Grade C). MOVEMENT COORDINATION IMPAIRMENTS (WAD) — Chronic: patient education combined with mobilization plus progressive submaximal cervicothoracic exercise using CBT principles; TENS (Grade C). HEADACHES — Acute: supervised active mobility exercise (Grade B); may use C1-2 self-SNAG exercise (Grade C). HEADACHES — Subacute: cervical manipulation and mobilization (Grade B). HEADACHES — Chronic: cervical/cervicothoracic manipulation/mobilization combined with shoulder girdle and neck stretching, strengthening, and endurance exercise (Grade B). RADIATING PAIN — Acute: may use mobilizing/stabilizing exercises, laser, and short-term cervical collar (Grade C). RADIATING PAIN — Chronic: mechanical intermittent cervical traction combined with stretching, strengthening, and cervical/thoracic mobilization/manipulation (Grade B); education and counseling to encourage participation in occupational and exercise activities (Grade B).",
    "notes": "2017 revision (updates 2008 CPG). Published J Orthop Sports Phys Ther. 2017;47(7):A1-A83. doi:10.2519/jospt.2017.0302. From APTA Orthopedics (Orthopaedic Section, American Physical Therapy Association). Authors: Blanpied PR, Gross AR, Elliott JM, Devaney LL, Clewley D, Walton DM, Sparks C, Robertson EK. Covers pathoanatomical features, imaging, examination, classification, and interventions for neck pain across 4 ICF-based subcategories. Literature search: January 2007 to August 2016."
